Data Types in Java:
    - to represent type of data, we have to use data types
    - Java is a strongly typed language, which means every variable must be declared with a data type.

Java data types fall into two main categories:

Primitive Data Types: (build in)
- Integer:
    1) byte (1 byte) - smallest integer type (byte b = 100)
    2) short (2 bytes) - small integer (short s = 5000)
    3) int (4 bytes) - default integer type (int i = 100000)
    4) long (8 bytes) - large integer (long l = 100000L)
- Floating:
    5) float (4 bytes) - single precision decimal (float f = 10.5f)
    6) double (8 bytes) - double precision decimal (double d = 20.99)
- Characters:
    7) char (2 bytes) - single character (unicode) (char c = 'A')
- Boolean:
    8) boolean (1 bit) - true, false (boolean b = true)


- Non Primitive (reference) data types: refers object and more complex structure
    1) String - sequence of characters (not primitive)
    2) Arrays - collection of similar data types
    3) Classes - user defined types
    4) Interfaces - used for abstraction
    5) Enums - fixed set of characters

- Type Conversion (casting)
    - Implicit or Widening (Automatic): int → long → float → double
        P a = x
        Q b = a
    - Explicit or Narrowing (Manual): double → float → long → int → short → byte
        P x = (Q) y